text:
NRL SuperCoach teams analysis round 1, 2017 Tom Sangster, The Daily Telegraph February 28, 2017 6:11pm 
SO a bunch of expected bargains fell over — including George Burgess, Curtis Scott and Moses Suli — but SuperCoaches still have enough cheapies to play the preferred “guns and rookies” strategy. 
NRL SuperCoach expert Tom Sangster analyses the Round 1 NRL teams. WINNERS 
Jayden Brailey - Rookie named starting hooker for the Sharks. Played 50 minutes in the World Club Challenge. 
Kaysa Pritchard - Seemingly named as an 80 minute hooker due to concussion fears over Isaac De Gois. However, Cameron King in jersey 18 will have plenty of SuperCoaches running scared. 
Tautau Moga - Cheapie named starting centre for the Broncos, with David Mead dropping to 18th man. 
Siosifa Taklaki - cheapie named in the centre spot of Aaron Gray (knee, round 10) at South Sydney. Dual position. 
Dean Whare - former New Zealand international starts cheap and scores a wing spot at the Panthers following injuries to Dallin Watene-Zelezniak (foot, round three) and Josh Mansour, (ACL, mid-season). 
Nick Cotric - Highly-rated rookie named to debut on the wing for the Raiders following exit of Edrick Lee (Sharks). 
Luke Yates/Sam Stone - Young forwards named on bench for Knights. Safer than most cheapie options in the forwards as Nathan Brown has shown he will give rookies big minutes - as shown by Daniel Saifiti (average 42 minutes) and Jacob Saifiti (58 minutes) last year. media_camera Johnathan Thurston, Shaun Johnson, Andrew Fifita and Cameron Smith. 
Dylan Phythian - Scores fullback spot at Knights, but also available at hooker for SuperCoach. 
Brock Lamb - Knights rookie is the only cheapie option at halfback. Great job security following Jarrod Mullen’s expected drugs ban. 
Brian Kelly - Cheapie scores Steve Matai’s left centre spot at Manly. 
Frank Winterstein/Lloyd Perrett - Winterstrein (starting back row) and Perrett (bench prop) earn spots in the Manly 17 following impressive pre-seasons. LOSERS 
Curtis Scott - Earmarked for a left centre spot at the Storm but lost out to Cheyse Blair following a poor defensive display in the final trial. 
Braidon Burns - Charity Shield revelation misses a backline spot at the Rabbitohs. 
George Burgess - Popular mid-ranger will now plummet in ownership after being named out of the 17. 
Moses Suli - Wests Tigers’$1.3m youngster misses the left wing spot created by the absence of Tim Simona (disciplinary, indefinite), despite awesome trial form. 
Jai Field - Misses vacant halfback spot at Dragons and will instead play as a bench utility. 
Kalyn Ponga - Coach Paul Green is taking SuperCoaches for a ride. He has named Antonio Winterstein (ankle), who was originally slated for round three. He’s also named all contenders for Winterstein’s spot in Ponga, Javid Bowen and Gideon Gela-Mosby. Keep an eye on final teams an hour before kick-off. 
Patrick Kaufusi/Sam Hoare - Kaufusi makes the 17, with Hoare in No. 18. Job security poor following signing of Shaun Fensom. SHARKS V BRONCOS
